### Fail-closed multimodal capture

Instrumentations MAY record a `StrippedPart` in `gen_ai.input.messages` /
`gen_ai.output.messages` to indicate that a non-text content part was detected
but its bytes were intentionally not captured. This is recommended whenever:

- The captured payload would exceed a configured size cap (`size_exceeded`).
- The modality is excluded from the configured allow-list (`modality_not_allowed`).
- A pre-upload redactor raised an error and the instrumentation chose to
  fail-closed rather than emit unredacted bytes (`redactor_error`).
- An upload to the configured object store failed (`upload_error`).
- No object store was configured but the instrumentation was asked to capture
  bytes (`no_store_configured`).

Recording a `StrippedPart` (rather than silently omitting the part) lets
downstream consumers distinguish *no media in this turn* from *media was
deliberately stripped*, which matters for compliance auditing and for
diagnosing capture-pipeline regressions.

When `BlobPart`, `FilePart`, or `UriPart` is recorded, the optional `byte_size`
field SHOULD be populated when known. This is useful for telemetry-on-telemetry
analysis (cost of capture, storage growth planning) without requiring consumers
to fetch the bytes.

> **Bytes-inline guidance.** `BlobPart` carries inline base64-encoded bytes.
> For deployments that prefer to keep telemetry pipelines small or that route
> binaries to operator-owned storage, `UriPart` referencing a blob in your own
> object store (S3 / MinIO / etc.) is the recommended pattern. The choice of
> part type itself encodes provenance: `BlobPart` = inline; `UriPart` = URI to
> a location the consumer can resolve; `FilePart` = file_id pre-uploaded to
> the provider.
